Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection

Unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comments Smallpox rashes on the hairless areas of the skin of the head, the inner surface of the front and rear legs, the udder skin, the scrotum, the inner surface of the tail, the mucous membranes and the reproductive organs. The appearance of red spots (roseola) with formation of red nodules (papules) is observed.

Control measures -Measures applied: Quarantine; Movement control inside the country

Vaccination in response to the outbreak (s)

Administrative division JALAL-ABAD vaccine
Species Sheep / goats
Total Vaccinated 4976
Details Live attenuated

Disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s); No treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied - No other measures

Laboratory name and type Republican Centre for Veterinary Diagnostic, Bishkek (National laboratory)

Species Sheep / goats
Test complement fixation test (CFT)
Test date 24/02/2012
Result Positive


Future Reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[Sheep and Goat Pox is comparatively common in the surrounding region with the following countries reporting the disease to OIE WAHID database since 2008: Afghanistan, Bangladesh, China, India, Iran,Kazakhstan, Mongolia, Nepal, Pakistan, Russia, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan. Additionally, some of these countries are reporting outbreaks in large numbers ranging from dozens per year to hundreds. This is the first time Kyrgyzstan has reported quantitative data but one suspects they may not have been reporting events previously.

The clinical description in this report indicates smallpox rashes which is a confusing term, at best, because smallpox only exists in two laboratories in the world and would be an extremely unlikely candidate as the cause of the pox rashes reported in this OIE report.

The generalized and typical pox lesions described here were almost certainly caused by a caprivirus, not the smallpox virus associated with human disease. Both sheep pox and goat pox are viral diseases of sheep and goats characterised by fever, generalised papules or nodules, vesicles (rarely), internal lesions (particularly in the lungs), and death. Both diseases are caused by strains of capripoxvirus, all of which can infect sheep and goats but not humans.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1HT*.]
